# ── Cargo build output ───────────────────────────────────────────────
/target

# ── Tauri-generated artifacts ────────────────────────────────────────
# `gen/` is rewritten by tauri-build / tauri-codegen on every build;
# checking it in causes merge conflicts and stale capability schemas.
/gen

# ── Bundled Next.js standalone tree (rebuilt by stage-standalone.mjs)
# Both the unpacked tree (used during dev / inspection) and the
# tarball that actually gets bundled by `tauri build`.
/resources/standalone
/resources/standalone.tar

# ── Bundled Node sidecar binaries ────────────────────────────────────
# These are large (~115MB each) and downloaded on demand — see
# binaries/README.md for the curl invocation. CI fetches them fresh
# during the macos-release.yml workflow.
/binaries/node
/binaries/node.exe
/binaries/node-*-apple-darwin
/binaries/node-*-pc-windows-msvc.exe

# ── Generated icons ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
# The icon set is generated by `tools/build_icons.py`, but it is intentionally
# committed: Tauri reads these paths directly during clean checkout builds.

# ── Rust scratch ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# rustfmt's pre-format backups. Harmless to commit but pure noise.
**/*.rs.bk

# NOTE: Cargo.lock is intentionally NOT ignored. Rust convention is
# to commit Cargo.lock for binary crates (which Tauri apps are) so
# every `cargo build` is reproducible across machines. Only library
# crates ignore it. If `Cargo.lock` was previously untracked here,
# `git add src-tauri/Cargo.lock` to start tracking it.
